Let me carefully check the Java code's logic. Original moveTo method:

public void moveTo(Box other) {
    if (num == 0) {
        return;
    } else if (num == 1) {
        num = 0;
        other.num++;
        if (red) {
            other.red = true;
        }
        red = false;
    } else {
        num--;
        other.num++;
        if (red) {
            other.red = true;
        }
    }
} Wait, in the case of num > 1, they decrement the current's num, increment the other's, and set the other's red to true if current was red.

Hence, the arrays in Fortran should be 1-based. Initialize the first box (index 1):

In Java, B[0] is initialized to 1 and red =true, so in Fortran:

num(1) = 1

red(1) = .true. Other boxes (from 2 to N) are initialized to num=1 (Java's Box(1, false))? Wait in Java: Box[] B = new Box[N];

for (int i=1; i<N; i++):

    B[i] = new Box(1, false);

So all boxes except B[0] start with 1 ball, and not red.
